04367nam a22006015i 9780812298369DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20222022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122983697 a10.9783/97808122983692doi  a(DE-B1597)590451  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aLIT0150002bisacsh1 aOrgel, Stephen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Invention of Shakespeare, and Other Essays /cStephen Orgel. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (176 p.) :b7 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Invention of Shakespeare -- t2. The Desire and Pursuit of the Whole -- t3. No Sense of an Ending -- t4. Lascivious Grace: Seductive Evil in Shakespeare and Jonson -- t5. The Poetics of Incomprehensibility -- t6. Two Household Friends: The Plausibility of Romeo and Juliet Q1 -- t7. Getting Things Wrong -- t8. Food for Thought -- t9. Revising King Lear -- t10. Venice at the Globe -- t11. Danny Scheie’s Shakespeare -- t12. Shakespeare all’italiana -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn his own time, Shakespeare was not a monument, but a man of the theater whose plays were less finished artifacts than works in process. In contrast to a book, a thing we have come to think of as final and achieved, a play is a work for performance, with each performance based only in part on a text we call a script. That script may well have had imperfections that the actors may or may not have noticed as they turned it into a performance. There were multiple versions of the scripts and never a "final" one. Every revival of a play—indeed, every subsequent performance—was and always will be different. Nevertheless, when we study Shakespeare, we are likely to come to him via printed texts that are scripts masquerading as books, and the impulse is to turn them into finished artifacts worthy of their author's dignity.In The Invention of Shakespeare, and Other Essays Stephen Orgel brings together twelve essays that consider the complex nature of Shakespearean texts, which often include errors or confusions, and the editorial and interpretive strategies for dealing with them in commentary or performance. "There is always some underlying claim that we are getting back to 'what Shakespeare actually wrote,'" Orgel writes, "but obviously that is not true: we clarify, we modernize, we undo muddles, we correct or explain (or explain away) errors, all in the interests of getting a clear, readable, unproblematic text. In short, we produce the text that we want him to, or think he must have written. But one thing we really do know about Shakespeare's original text is that it was hard to read."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Shakespeare.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aLiterature.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076767440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812298369423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780812298369/original  a978-3-11-076767-4  University of Pennsylvania Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK